picoctf tea-cash writeup

1.you need to understand glibc and tcache in this challenge 

2.if we need to run this binary file , we need to patch it (because your system might not fit it , namely glibc)

=> use "strings heapedit | grep -i glibc." to find which glibc version did it use (but it is not always correct , this is king of clue)

=> download glibc data , just use "git clone" to clone which you like it (version is 2.27)

=> download patchelf by using "sudo apt install patchelf"

=> use "patchelf --set-interpreter ./ld-2.27.so ./heapedit" to adjust inerpreter 

=> use "patchelf --set-rpath . ./heapedit" to adjust run libc position

=> chmod +x ld-2.27.so 

3.now , you can run the file , we can analyze it source code 

4.know we need to input a pointer 6 times and it will give us first

5.so we write a script (tea-cash.py) and use gdb to analyze it 

=> we can just input first head pointer
=> use "vmmap heap" to look where start of heap
=> use "x/gx $(your_first_address)"

6.we can know that it compare our input and previous address data , so we just input address and look this address data and input next time

7.after several times of input , we can know that our input address increase 0x90 every time

8.we can adjust our script (tea-cash.py) and run it

